Intuitively, the way an unregulated bank works is something like this. You =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the shareholder and chief executive officer =E2=80=94=C2=A0s=
tart a bank and put up $10 of your own money as initial capital. The bank h=
as $10 of shareholder equity, takes $100 of deposits and makes $110 of loan=
s. If the loans get paid back with interest, then the bank ends up with, sa=
y, $116, it pays $103 to its depositors (with interest), and you get your $=
10 back with $3 of profits. If $20 worth of the loans default, then the ban=
k has only $90 (plus some interest, so, say, $94); the depositors get back =
94 cents on the dollar and you lose everything.
But this all happens over time. The bank borrows short to lend long: The de=
positors can ask for their=C2=A0money back at any time, but most days most =
of them don=E2=80=99t, so the bank can make long-term loans that pay higher=
 interest. One thing this means is that if all of the bank=E2=80=99s loans =
are perfectly good, but all the depositors ask for their money back at once=
, the bank won=E2=80=99t have it; it will have to sell its loans at discoun=
ted prices to raise money, and the depositors will end up getting back less=
 than they put in. The =E2=80=9Crun on the bank=E2=80=9D will itself cause =
the depositors (and shareholders) to lose money.
Conversely, another thing it means is that if a bunch of the bank=E2=80=99s=
 loans default, you will =E2=80=A6=C2=A0uh =E2=80=A6=C2=A0want to avoid men=
tioning that? Like, if you just go out and say =E2=80=9C$20 of our money is=
 gone, sorry,=E2=80=9D then depositors=C2=A0will=C2=A0ask for all of their =
money back at once, and (1) you only have $90 of assets to pay back $100 of=
 deposits, (2) even those loans have to be sold at a discount to raise mone=
y, so in a run on the bank you=E2=80=99ll only be able to pay back, say, 70=
 cents on the dollar, and (3) definitely the bank will be bankrupt and shar=
eholders will lose everything.=C2=A0
On the other hand, if you go out and say =E2=80=9Csmall hiccup but we are f=
inancially secure, everything is fine,=E2=80=9D then maybe the depositors=
=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0ask for their money back all at once, and you will=
 have a chance to earn back the losses. You take in short-term deposits, yo=
u make long-term loans, you make a profit each quarter, and that profit goe=
s to building your assets back up until you have enough to pay back all the=
 depositors. In the good times, after all, this is a profitable business, s=
o if you can keep going long enough then everything could work out.
How specifically you do this will depend on how sophisticated and demanding=
 your depositors are. =E2=80=9CLa=C2=A0la=C2=A0la everything=E2=80=99s grea=
t, stop asking questions=E2=80=9D will work in some cases. In other cases, =
your investors will demand financial statements, lists of assets, etc., but=
 there are still things you can do. For instance if you had $110 of loans a=
nd $20 worth of them defaulted, now you have $90 of assets and $100 of depo=
sits, oops. But you can=C2=A0create=C2=A0more assets. You can write an IOU =
to your bank, a promissory note saying=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe shareholder of thi=
s bank promises to pay the bank $20.=E2=80=9D Now the bank has $90 of regul=
ar loans and a $20 loan to you,
  [1]
 for a total of $110 of loans and $100 of deposits. The bank is solvent and=
 everything is fine. Things keep going along, the bank makes loans and earn=
s profits, and you get those profits and use them to pay back the IOU.=C2=
=A0
In the general case that IOU might not have a ton of economic substance: If=
 you promise to pay your bank $20, and you don=E2=80=99t have $20, that IOU=
 isn=E2=80=99t worth much, or at least, isn=E2=80=99t worth much=C2=A0now. =
But if everyone says =E2=80=9Cah, yes, it=E2=80=99s fine, this bank is well=
 capitalized,=E2=80=9D then they won=E2=80=99t withdraw their money, and th=
e bank will continue along, and hopefully you won=E2=80=99t make any more=
=C2=A0bad loans, and hopefully it will be profitable, and if that goes on f=
or long enough then the profits will add up to more than $20 and you=E2=80=
=99ll pay back the IOU.=C2=A0
In other words, the IOU is valuable if=C2=A0both=C2=A0(1) people believe in=
 it=C2=A0and=C2=A0(2) you do a better job managing the bank now than you di=
d before. If you=C2=A0keep=C2=A0making lots of loans that default, you=E2=
=80=99re gonna have problems.
None of this is banking advice, or even all that=C2=A0relevant=C2=A0to the =
actual US banking industry. Actual banking has things like lenders of last =
resort and deposit insurance, so bank runs are less of a practical problem.=
 And it has capital and safety-and-soundness regulation to try to prevent b=
anks from losing 20% of their loan book, and to shut them down if they do. =
And it has disclosure and related-party regulations that look with suspicio=
n on bankers writing IOUs to themselves.
But it sure is relevant to crypto shadow banking! We talk about it a bunch,=
 in different forms. For instance there is   the story from a few years bac=
k about Bitfinex and Tether. Bitfinex is a crypto exchange, Tether is a sta=
blecoin issuer, they are affiliated companies, and in 2018 they had an oops=
ie where Bitfinex lost a lot of customer money at a shady Panamanian money =
transmitter. If Bitfinex had gone out to its customers and said=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Chey we lost a bunch of your money,=E2=80=9D that would have been bad; th=
ey might have withdrawn the rest of their money. In fact they=C2=A0were=C2=
=A0withdrawing a lot of money, and Bitfinex was short on cash. So Bitfinex =
took $625 million from Tether, enough cash to pay out withdrawals. But that=
 left Tether undercapitalized: It had issued a bunch of stablecoins that we=
re supposed to be backed by $1 of assets per stablecoin, but now Bitfinex h=
ad taken $625 million of Tether=E2=80=99s cash to pay out its customers. So=
 Tether was no longer fully backed.
Ah, but it was! See, technically, Tether was backed by (1) all the assets i=
t had previously=C2=A0had, (2) minus $625 million of cash, (3) plus a $625 =
million IOU from Bitfinex. If Bitfinex could return to profitability and st=
op losing money to Panamanian money transmitters, everything would be fine.=
=C2=A0
This basically=C2=A0worked:=C2=A0There was no run on Tether, Bitfinex and T=
ether are both pretty lucrative businesses, and eventually the $625 million=
 hole seems to have been closed. Tether got in trouble for it =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it was sued by the New York attorney general and eventually settled =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0because this accounting is not, you know, super=C2=A0legitimate=
. =E2=80=9CTether is 100% backed by real dollar assets=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9CTether is partly backed by an unsecured IOU from its sister company=E2=
=80=9D are almost=C2=A0the same, but not quite, and a traditional financial=
 lawyer might be appalled by the difference. But a crypto shadow bank, ehh.
Or we have   talked a few   times about crypto lending platforms that blew =
up in very visible fashion last summer: They took deposits, they used the d=
eposits to make loans, the loans went bad, the depositors panicked, they as=
ked for their money back, the money wasn=E2=80=99t there. Writing IOUs to t=
hemselves, at that point, would not have helped much; nobody would have tru=
sted an IOU from the shareholders of Voyager or Celsius or BlockFi. But wha=
t could=C2=A0help was agreeing to a bailout from some other, more stable-se=
eming crypto firm. (Generally, this summer, that firm was FTX, oops.) The w=
ay this worked was not generally that the acquirer would come in with enoug=
h cash to pay out 100% of the lending platform=E2=80=99s depositors. Instea=
d, the acquirer would just=C2=A0promise=C2=A0enough cash to pay all the dep=
ositors, and then the depositors would say =E2=80=9Coh that=E2=80=99s fine =
then=E2=80=9D and not withdraw their money. In an ideal world, the platform=
 stays in business, it makes profits, it stops making bad loans, and it mak=
es enough profits to fill up the hole so that the acquirer never needs to p=
ay anyone out. That is not really how things worked out, with the FTX bailo=
uts, but that was the idea.
Or there is Genesis. Genesis Global Capital LLC is a crypto lending firm th=
at is part of Digital Currency Group Inc., a collection of crypto businesse=
s run by Barry Silbert; other DCG entities include Grayscale Investments LL=
C, which runs a lucrative business of exchange-traded crypto trusts. Genesi=
s is an institutional lending firm =E2=80=94=C2=A0it takes money from big i=
nvestors and lends it to hedge funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0but a big chunk of its =
money came from Gemini Earn, a retail crypto lending product run by the Win=
klevoss twins=E2=80=99 crypto exchange, Gemini. In November, Genesis stoppe=
d repaying its depositors, including Gemini Earn customers, and recently Ca=
meron Winklevoss has been writing public letters complaining about this. He=
   sent another one today, asking DCG to fire Silbert, and it complains abo=
ut exactly this sort of IOU transaction:

Genesis lent $2.36=C2=A0billion of assets to 3AC, a Singapore-based hedge f=
und that went belly up in June 2022. After collateral was liquidated, Genes=
is indicated that it was left with a loss of at least $1.2 billion. At this=
 point, Barry Silbert had two legitimate options: restructure the Genesis l=
oan book (inside or outside of bankruptcy court) or fill the $1.2 billion h=
ole. He did neither. =E2=80=A6 Instead, he pretended to. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0
On July 6th, Michael Moro, then-CEO of Genesis, tweeted: =E2=80=9CDCG has a=
ssumed certain liabilities of Genesis related to [3AC] to ensure we have th=
e capital to operate and scale our business for the long-term.=E2=80=9D
This statement was false and misleading. In reality, DCG had=C2=A0not ensur=
ed that Genesis had the capital to operate. In fact, DCG hadn=E2=80=99t giv=
en Genesis so much as a penny of actual funding to make up for the 3AC loss=
es. Instead, DCG entered into a 10-year promissory note with Genesis at an =
interest rate of 1% =E2=80=94=C2=A0due in 2032. This note was a complete gi=
mmick that did nothing to improve Genesis=E2=80=99s immediate liquidity pos=
ition or make its balance sheet solvent.=C2=A0

I disagree? The note was a complete gimmick that obviously=C2=A0improved Ge=
nesis=E2=80=99s immediate liquidity position.
  [2]
 If DCG had=C2=A0not=C2=A0given Genesis this IOU, then Genesis would have b=
een insolvent, its investors would have demanded their money back, there wo=
uld have been a run on the bank and that would have been very bad for liqui=
dity. But it did give Genesis the IOU, so nobody demanded their money back,=
 so liquidity was fine! It=E2=80=99s a=C2=A0gimmick, sure, but it=E2=80=99s=
 sort of the standard gimmick of crypto shadow banking, and it =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0uh =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, I guess it could work?
It ended up not working all that well here. As I said above, for this gimmi=
ck to work, you need two things: The market has to trust the IOU, and you h=
ave to stop losing money on bad loans. As far as I can tell, Genesis satisf=
ied the first condition: DCG wrote it a $1.1 billion IOU in July, and custo=
mers=C2=A0like the Winklevoss twins=C2=A0decided that was good enough, so  =
they did not withdraw their (clients=E2=80=99) money. But it did not satisf=
y the second: When FTX collapsed in November, Genesis had more exposure, an=
d had to shut down withdrawals anyway. If you trusted the IOU in July, you =
probably feel foolish now. Winklevoss sure seems to.

