There are some public companies where the chief executive officer (and, usu=
ally, founder) is also the controlling shareholder. This creates a weird dy=
namic for those companies=E2=80=99 boards. What if the CEO does something b=
ad, and the board concludes that he should no longer run the company? Ordin=
arily, in that scenario, the board would fire the CEO. But here the CEO is =
the controlling shareholder, and he can fire the board.=C2=A0
There is a correct answer here, which is that, if the board concludes that =
it is no longer in the best interests of the company and its shareholders f=
or the CEO to be in charge, they should fire him. They have a fiduciary dut=
y to run the company with loyalty and care; they can=E2=80=99t make a decis=
ion that they think is wrong just because they=E2=80=99re afraid of losing =
their board seats. Then of course the CEO =E2=80=94=C2=A0er, ex-CEO =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0can fire them, and re-hire himself,  but that=E2=80=99s life:

Vince McMahon, the majority owner and former chief executive of World Wrest=
ling Entertainment Inc., who retired last year amid a misconduct probe, has=
 returned to the company and is pursuing a possible sale of the business.
Mr. McMahon, who has majority voting power through his ownership of WWE=E2=
=80=99s Class-B stock, said Thursday he had told the company that he is ele=
cting himself and two former co-presidents and directors, Michelle Wilson a=
nd George Barrios, to the board, confirming an earlier Wall Street Journal =
report. The board had previously rebuffed a move to reinstate Mr. McMahon.
WWE said in a news release Friday that Mr. McMahon had removed JoEllen Lyon=
s Dillon, Jeffrey R. Speed and Alan M. Wexler from the board. In addition, =
Ignace Lahoud and Man Jit Singh had resigned as board members, effective Fr=
iday, the company said. =E2=80=A6
Mr. McMahon, whose abrupt departure in July 2022 followed disclosures by th=
e Journal of multiple payouts to women who had alleged sexual misconduct an=
d infidelity, expects he will be able to assume the role of executive chair=
man, though he would need board approval for that, the people said.=C2=A0

McMahon =E2=80=9Cvoluntarily stepped back from his responsibilities as CEO=
=E2=80=9D in June, and=C2=A0 resigned entirely in July, to be replaced by c=
o-CEOs including his daughter. Now that he=E2=80=99s back, he has  disclose=
d some of his recent correspondence with the old board. On Dec. 20, he  wro=
te to the board saying that he had changed his mind and wanted to come back=
 as executive chairman. On Dec. 27, the board wrote back  to say no thanks:

As you know, it is our fiduciary obligation to continue to act in a way we =
believe is in the best interests of the Company and its shareholders. We ha=
ve always taken that responsibility very seriously and all of our decisions=
 are guided by this duty. ...
Although we welcome your participation in the launch of a strategic alterna=
tives review process, it is also our unanimous view that your return to the=
 Company at this time, while government investigations into your conduct by=
 the U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office and SEC are still pending, would not be=
 prudent from a shareholder value perspective. This determination is based =
on a variety of factors, including non-public information the Board has bec=
ome aware of and the risks to the Company and its shareholders of placing a=
 greater spotlight on these issues.

On Dec. 31,  he disagreed:
There is no rationale for your position that my return to the Company =E2=
=80=9Cwould not be prudent from a shareholder value perspective.=E2=80=9D T=
o the contrary, my return in the context of the media rights negotiations a=
nd a potential value maximizing strategic transaction is necessary precisel=
y from a shareholder value perspective because it will allow WWE (as well a=
s any transaction counterparties) to engage in these processes knowing they=
 will have the support of the controlling shareholder.=C2=A0
On Jan. 5 I guess he got tired of this exchange, so he=C2=A0fired three boa=
rd members and  appointed himself back to the board. He can  just do that! =
He owns ( 81% of the voting power of) the company. The stock is up more tha=
n 20% since then, so WWE=E2=80=99s (non-McMahon) shareholders seem to agree=
 with him, and disagree with the old board, about who provides the most sha=
reholder value.
It is a funny correspondence. You might think that the exchange between the=
 81% shareholder and the board might go like:

Shareholder: I want to come back, and I control 81% of the votes, so.
Board: Sure do, boss, welcome back!

But in fact McMahon=E2=80=99s letters to the board barely mention his abili=
ty to fire the directors; they letters are all about what is best for the c=
ompany and its shareholders. And the board said no to him, even though he c=
ould fire them, and quickly did.
One takeaway might just be that everyone here has good lawyers: You always =
want to create a good=C2=A0record, in which everyone says that they are mot=
ivated only by shareholder value and not by raw power. Also, though, if you=
 are a director who got rid of McMahon, and he wants to come back, what is =
the upside to saying yes? You won=E2=80=99t have a pleasant time at board m=
eetings; presumably he=E2=80=99ll still be mad at you for getting rid of hi=
m. And if things go poorly, shareholders will complain: =E2=80=9CYou though=
t he was a danger to the company when he left, but then you let him back a =
few months later?=E2=80=9D Really the simplest solution is to have him fire=
 you so you don=E2=80=99t have deal with it anymore.

