10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Gemini vs. Genesis</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively, the way an unregulated bank works=
 is something like this. You =E2=80=94=C2=A0the shareholder and chief execu=
tive officer =E2=80=94=C2=A0start a bank and put up $10 of your own money a=
s initial capital. The bank has $10 of shareholder equity, takes $100 of de=
posits and makes $110 of loans. If the loans get paid back with interest, t=
hen the bank ends up with, say, $116, it pays $103 to its depositors (with =
interest), and you get your $10 back with $3 of profits. If $20 worth of th=
e loans default, then the bank has only $90 (plus some interest, so, say, $=
94); the depositors get back 94 cents on the dollar and you lose everything=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this all happens over time. The bank borro=
ws short to lend long: The depositors can ask for their=C2=A0money back at =
any time, but most days most of them don=E2=80=99t, so the bank can make lo=
ng-term loans that pay higher interest. One thing this means is that if all=
 of the bank=E2=80=99s loans are perfectly good, but all the depositors ask=
 for their money back at once, the bank won=E2=80=99t have it; it will have=
 to sell its loans at discounted prices to raise money, and the depositors =
will end up getting back less than they put in. The =E2=80=9Crun on the ban=
k=E2=80=9D will itself cause the depositors (and shareholders) to lose mone=
y.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Conversely, another thing it means is that if =
a bunch of the bank=E2=80=99s loans default, you will =E2=80=A6=C2=A0uh =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0want to avoid mentioning that? Like, if you just go out and say=
 =E2=80=9C$20 of our money is gone, sorry,=E2=80=9D then depositors=C2=A0<e=
m>will=C2=A0</em>ask for all of their money back at once, and (1) you only =
have $90 of assets to pay back $100 of deposits, (2) even those loans have =
to be sold at a discount to raise money, so in a run on the bank you=E2=80=
=99ll only be able to pay back, say, 70 cents on the dollar, and (3) defini=
tely the bank will be bankrupt and shareholders will lose everything.=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, if you go out and say =E2=
=80=9Csmall hiccup but we are financially secure, everything is fine,=E2=80=
=9D then maybe the depositors=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>ask for thei=
r money back all at once, and you will have a chance to earn back the losse=
s. You take in short-term deposits, you make long-term loans, you make a pr=
ofit each quarter, and that profit goes to building your assets back up unt=
il you have enough to pay back all the depositors. In the good times, after=
 all, this is a profitable business, so if you can keep going long enough t=
hen everything could work out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How specifically you do this will depend on ho=
w sophisticated and demanding your depositors are. =E2=80=9CLa=C2=A0la=C2=
=A0la everything=E2=80=99s great, stop asking questions=E2=80=9D will work =
in some cases. In other cases, your investors will demand financial stateme=
nts, lists of assets, etc., but there are still things you can do. For inst=
ance if you had $110 of loans and $20 worth of them defaulted, now you have=
 $90 of assets and $100 of deposits, oops. But you can=C2=A0<em>create=C2=
=A0</em>more assets. You can write an IOU to your bank, a promissory note s=
aying=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe shareholder of this bank promises to pay the bank $=
20.=E2=80=9D Now the bank has $90 of regular loans and a $20 loan to you,<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> for a total of $110 of loans and $100 of deposits. The bank is solvent=
 and everything is fine. Things keep going along, the bank makes loans and =
earns profits, and you get those profits and use them to pay back the IOU.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the general case that IOU might not have a =
ton of economic substance: If you promise to pay your bank $20, and you don=
=E2=80=99t have $20, that IOU isn=E2=80=99t worth much, or at least, isn=E2=
=80=99t worth much=C2=A0<em>now</em>. But if everyone says =E2=80=9Cah, yes=
, it=E2=80=99s fine, this bank is well capitalized,=E2=80=9D then they won=
=E2=80=99t withdraw their money, and the bank will continue along, and hope=
fully you won=E2=80=99t make any <em>more=C2=A0</em>bad loans, and hopefull=
y it will be profitable, and if that goes on for long enough then the profi=
ts will add up to more than $20 and you=E2=80=99ll pay back the IOU.=C2=A0<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other words, the IOU is valuable if=C2=A0<e=
m>both=C2=A0</em>(1) people believe in it=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>(2) you do=
 a better job managing the bank now than you did before. If you=C2=A0<em>ke=
ep=C2=A0</em>making lots of loans that default, you=E2=80=99re gonna have p=
roblems.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of this is banking advice, or even all th=
at=C2=A0relevant=C2=A0to the actual US banking industry. Actual banking has=
 things like lenders of last resort and deposit insurance, so bank runs are=
 less of a practical problem. And it has capital and safety-and-soundness r=
egulation to try to prevent banks from losing 20% of their loan book, and t=
o shut them down if they do. And it has disclosure and related-party regula=
tions that look with suspicion on bankers writing IOUs to themselves.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it sure is relevant to crypto shadow banki=
ng! We talk about it a bunch, in different forms. For instance there is <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30210082.274519/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDQtMjYvdGhpbmdz=
LWdvdC13ZWlyZC1mb3Itc3RhYmxlY29pbi10ZXRoZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExMDIzX01PTkVZU1R=
VRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMT=
EwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4242900b" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  the story from a few years back</a> about Bitfinex and Tether. Bitfine=
x is a crypto exchange, Tether is a stablecoin issuer, they are affiliated =
companies, and in 2018 they had an oopsie where Bitfinex lost a lot of cust=
omer money at a shady Panamanian money transmitter. If Bitfinex had gone ou=
t to its customers and said=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chey we lost a bunch of your money=
,=E2=80=9D that would have been bad; they might have withdrawn the rest of =
their money. In fact they=C2=A0<em>were=C2=A0</em>withdrawing a lot of mone=
y, and Bitfinex was short on cash. So Bitfinex took $625 million from Tethe=
r, enough cash to pay out withdrawals. But that left Tether undercapitalize=
d: It had issued a bunch of stablecoins that were supposed to be backed by =
$1 of assets per stablecoin, but now Bitfinex had taken $625 million of Tet=
her=E2=80=99s cash to pay out its customers. So Tether was no longer fully =
backed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ah, but it was! See, technically, Tether was b=
acked by (1) all the assets it had previously=C2=A0had, (2) minus $625 mill=
ion of cash, (3) plus a $625 million IOU from Bitfinex. If Bitfinex could r=
eturn to profitability and stop losing money to Panamanian money transmitte=
rs, everything would be fine.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This basically=C2=A0<em>worked:=C2=A0</em>Ther=
e was no run on Tether, Bitfinex and Tether are both pretty lucrative busin=
esses, and eventually the $625 million hole seems to have been closed. Teth=
er got in trouble for it =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was sued by the New York attorne=
y general and eventually settled =E2=80=94=C2=A0because this accounting is =
not, you know, <em>super</em>=C2=A0legitimate. =E2=80=9CTether is 100% back=
ed by real dollar assets=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CTether is partly backed by a=
n unsecured IOU from its sister company=E2=80=9D are <em>almost=C2=A0</em>t=
he same, but not quite, and a traditional financial lawyer might be appalle=
d by the difference. But a crypto shadow bank, ehh.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or we have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/30210082.274519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMTkvZWxvbi13YW50cy1zb21lLXR3aXR0ZXItaGVscD9j=
bXBpZD1CQkQwMTEwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV=
3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB4c07b9eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked</a> a few <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30210082.274519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMjgvZnR4LXMtYmxvY2tmaS1yZXNjdWUt=
ZGlkbi10LXdvcms_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ=
1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leX=
N0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB372f70f8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  times</a> about crypto=
 lending platforms that blew up in very visible fashion last summer: They t=
ook deposits, they used the deposits to make loans, the loans went bad, the=
 depositors panicked, they asked for their money back, the money wasn=E2=80=
=99t there. Writing IOUs to themselves, at that point, would not have helpe=
d much; nobody would have trusted an IOU from the shareholders of Voyager o=
r Celsius or BlockFi. But what <em>could=C2=A0</em>help was agreeing to a b=
ailout from some other, more stable-seeming crypto firm. (Generally, this s=
ummer, that firm was FTX, oops.) The way this worked was not generally that=
 the acquirer would come in with enough cash to pay out 100% of the lending=
 platform=E2=80=99s depositors. Instead, the acquirer would just=C2=A0<em>p=
romise=C2=A0</em>enough cash to pay all the depositors, and then the deposi=
tors would say =E2=80=9Coh that=E2=80=99s fine then=E2=80=9D and not withdr=
aw their money. In an ideal world, the platform stays in business, it makes=
 profits, it stops making bad loans, and it makes enough profits to fill up=
 the hole so that the acquirer never needs to pay anyone out. That is not r=
eally how things worked out, with the FTX bailouts, but that was the idea.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or there is Genesis. Genesis Global Capital LL=
C is a crypto lending firm that is part of Digital Currency Group Inc., a c=
ollection of crypto businesses run by Barry Silbert; other DCG entities inc=
lude Grayscale Investments LLC, which runs a lucrative business of exchange=
-traded crypto trusts. Genesis is an institutional lending firm =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it takes money from big investors and lends it to hedge funds =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but a big chunk of its money came from Gemini Earn, a retail crypt=
o lending product run by the Winklevoss twins=E2=80=99 crypto exchange, Gem=
ini. In November, Genesis stopped repaying its depositors, including Gemini=
 Earn customers, and recently Cameron Winklevoss has been writing public le=
tters complaining about this. He <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30210082.274519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTAvZ2VtaW5pLXMtd2lua2xldm9zcy1kZW1hbmRzLXJlbW92YWwtb2Y=
tZGNnLWNlby1iYXJyeS1zaWxiZXJ0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZW=
RpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDExMCZ1dG1fY2Ftc=
GFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB585aa40b" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  sent ano=
ther one today</a>, asking DCG to fire Silbert, and it complains about exac=
tly this sort of IOU transaction:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Genesis lent $2.36=C2=A0billion of assets to 3=
AC, a Singapore-based hedge fund that went belly up in June 2022. After col=
lateral was liquidated, Genesis indicated that it was left with a loss of a=
t least $1.2 billion. At this point, Barry Silbert had two legitimate optio=
ns: restructure the Genesis loan book (inside or outside of bankruptcy cour=
t) or fill the $1.2 billion hole. He did neither. =E2=80=A6 Instead, he pre=
tended to. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On July 6th, Michael Moro, then-CEO of Genesis=
, tweeted: =E2=80=9CDCG has assumed certain liabilities of Genesis related =
to [3AC] to ensure we have the capital to operate and scale our business fo=
r the long-term.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This statement was false and misleading. In re=
ality, DCG had=C2=A0<em>not </em>ensured that Genesis had the capital to op=
erate. In fact, DCG hadn=E2=80=99t given Genesis so much as a penny of actu=
al funding to make up for the 3AC losses. Instead, DCG entered into a 10-ye=
ar promissory note with Genesis at an interest rate of 1% =E2=80=94=C2=A0du=
e in <em>2032</em>. This note was a complete gimmick that did nothing to im=
prove Genesis=E2=80=99s immediate liquidity position or make its balance sh=
eet solvent.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I disagree? The note was a complete gimmick th=
at <em>obviously=C2=A0</em>improved Genesis=E2=80=99s immediate liquidity p=
osition.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> If DCG had=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>given Genesis this IOU, then Genesis=
 would have been insolvent, its investors would have demanded their money b=
ack, there would have been a run on the bank and that would have been very =
bad for liquidity. But it did give Genesis the IOU, so nobody demanded thei=
r money back, so liquidity was fine! It=E2=80=99s a=C2=A0<em>gimmick</em>, =
sure, but it=E2=80=99s sort of the standard gimmick of crypto shadow bankin=
g, and it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0uh =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, I guess it could work?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It ended up not working all that well here. As=
 I said above, for this gimmick to work, you need two things: The market ha=
s to trust the IOU, <em>and</em> you have to stop losing money on bad loans=
. As far as I can tell, Genesis satisfied the first condition: DCG wrote it=
 a $1.1 billion IOU in July, and customers=C2=A0<em>like the Winklevoss twi=
ns=C2=A0</em>decided that was good enough, so <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/30210082.274519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlaW5mb3JtYXR=
pb24uY29tL2FydGljbGVzL2luc2lkZS10aGUtcmlzZS1hbmQtZmFsbC1vZi1nZW1pbmlzLXJpc2=
t5LWVhcm4tYWNjb3VudHMtdGhhdC1sZWZ0LTkwMC1taWxsaW9uLW9mLWN1c3RvbWVyLW1vbmV5L=
WluLWxpbWJvP3JjPTFiZGk1aA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBced9741c" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> they =
did not withdraw their (clients=E2=80=99) money</a>. But it did not satisfy=
 the second: When FTX collapsed in November, Genesis had more exposure, and=
 had to shut down withdrawals anyway. If you trusted the IOU in July, you p=
robably feel foolish now. Winklevoss sure seems to.</p>
