oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 81% of the vot=
ing power of</a>) the company. The stock is up more than 20% since then, so=
 WWE=E2=80=99s (non-McMahon) shareholders seem to agree with him, and disag=
ree with the old board, about who provides the most shareholder value.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is a funny correspondence. You might think =
that the exchange between the 81% shareholder and the board might go like:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Shareholder: </strong>I want to come b=
ack, and I control 81% of the votes, so.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board:</strong> Sure do, boss, welcome=
 back!</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in fact McMahon=E2=80=99s letters to the b=
oard barely mention his ability to fire the directors; they letters are all=
 about what is best for the company and its shareholders. And the board sai=
d no to him, even though he could fire them, and quickly did.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One takeaway might just be that everyone here =
has good lawyers: You always want to create a good=C2=A0<em>record</em>, in=
 which everyone says that they are motivated only by shareholder value and =
not by raw power. Also, though, if you are a director who got rid of McMaho=
n, and he wants to come back, what is the upside to saying yes? You won=E2=
=80=99t have a pleasant time at board meetings; presumably he=E2=80=99ll st=
ill be mad at you for getting rid of him. And if things go poorly, sharehol=
ders will complain: =E2=80=9CYou thought he was a danger to the company whe=
n he left, but then you let him back a few months later?=E2=80=9D Really th=
e simplest solution is to have him fire you so you don=E2=80=99t have deal =
with it anymore.</p>
